# Text ASCII Safety

Use plain ASCII in all authored content: code, config, text, manpages,
commit messages, PR titles/bodies, issue comments, and review comments.
This applies to every file type we control, including documentation,
markdown, comments, and generated text. There are no doc-only exceptions.

- Forbid typographic Unicode often produced by AI:
  - em dash (U+2014)
  - en dash (U+2013)
  - curly double/single quotes (U+201C, U+201D, U+2018, U+2019)
  - bullet/dot punctuation used as bullets (U+2022, U+25E6, U+00B7)
  - arrows (U+2192, U+2190, U+2194, U+21D2, U+21D4)
  - ellipsis (U+2026), non-breaking hyphen (U+2011), no-break space (U+00A0)

- Hidden/invisible characters are forbidden in all files, including docs:
  - zero-width chars (`U+200B`..`U+200D`, `U+FEFF`)
  - bidirectional controls (`U+202A`..`U+202E`, `U+2066`..`U+2069`)
  - any other non-printing Unicode control chars (except newline/tab where valid)

- If a forbidden char is found, replace it with ASCII:
  - dashes to `-`, curly single quotes to `'`, curly double quotes to `"`, and bullets/arrows to `-` or words.

## Mandatory Review Check

When performing a code review, run one of these checks depending on scope.
Run from the repository root so paths from git resolve. The patterns below use
a shell loop instead of GNU `xargs -r` (not available on BSD/macOS `xargs`).

Skip vendored, build, and git metadata trees (not project-authored): `3rdparty/`,
`dist/`, and `.git/`. Add more `--glob '!**/DIR/**'` entries if you introduce other
large third-party or generated trees.

**Staged changes only (default for pre-commit review):**

```bash
git diff --cached --diff-filter=ACMR --name-only \
    | while IFS= read -r f; do
        case "$f" in
            3rdparty/* | dist/* | .git/*) continue ;;
        esac
        [ -n "$f" ] && rg -n "[^\x09\x0A\x20-\x7E]" -- "$f"
    done
```

**Commit range (user specifies BASE..HEAD):**

```bash
git diff BASE..HEAD --diff-filter=ACMR --name-only \
    | while IFS= read -r f; do
        case "$f" in
            3rdparty/* | dist/* | .git/*) continue ;;
        esac
        [ -n "$f" ] && rg -n "[^\x09\x0A\x20-\x7E]" -- "$f"
    done
```

**Full repository scan:**

```bash
rg -n "[^\x09\x0A\x20-\x7E]" . \
    --glob '!.git/**' \
    --glob '!3rdparty/**' \
    --glob '!dist/**'
```

The regex allowlist covers only safe, visible ASCII:

| Range | Chars | Purpose |
|-------|-------|---------|
| `\x09` | Tab (HT) | Indentation (Makefiles, configs) |
| `\x0A` | Line Feed (LF) | Unix newline |
| `\x20-\x7E` | Space through `~` | All printable ASCII: letters, digits, punctuation, symbols |

Everything outside that set is flagged, including:

- `\x00-\x08`: null and control chars
- `\x0B-\x0C`: vertical tab, form feed
- `\x0D`: carriage return (unsafe in Unix projects)
- `\x0E-\x1F`: remaining control chars
- `\x7F`: DEL
- `\x80+`: all non-ASCII (Unicode, multibyte, extended)

- Treat any match as a finding unless it is an explicitly approved exception.
- Report each finding with file path, snippet, risk, and ASCII-safe replacement.
